Hedonic Home Price Prediction

Al-Jalil Gault & Ejirooghene Ojeni, Master of City Planning, â€™21

October 15, 2020

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to create an efficient, data-driven way to predict home sale price in Miami, FL for the company Zillow. Today, the real estate market is very subjective. The factors that influence the price of a home vary across region and neighborhood, so it becomes a difficult task to assess. Additionally, the use of data science can help with operational efficiency because, if you can program an algorithm to make predictions for a municipality, this alleviates the cost of sending property assessors across the entire city.

Generally, there are three types of variables which impact the sale price of a home. Those include: Internal Characteristics, Public Amenities and Services, and Spatial Structure. Internal characteristics are features of a home such as number of bedrooms or bathrooms. Public amenities and services are things like access to a beach or public transportation. Spatial structure variables are spatial occurrences, such as neighborhood culture, population, or distance to water.

This project uses these types of variables to identify factors that influence home sale price most significantly. The results of this model must substantially improve before it is ready for civic use. This report features some of the successes with predictive variables as well as ways to check for the most equitable deployment possible.

tracts18.2 <-  
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B19001_001E","B01003_001E","B15003_022E"), 
          year=2018, state=12, county=086, geometry=T) %>% 
  st_transform('ESRI:102728')

tracts18.2 <- 
  tracts18.2 %>%
  dplyr::select( -NAME, -moe) %>%
  spread(variable, estimate) %>%
  dplyr::select(-geometry) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01003_001, 
         HHIncome = B19001_001,
         BacAttain = B15003_022)

tracts18.2$Totalarea <- st_area(tracts18.2$geometry) #calculate the area of a census tract
tracts18.2$Totalarea_Miles <- tracts18.2$Totalarea / 27878400 #convert the area into units of miles
tracts18.2$PopDens <- tracts18.2$TotalPop /tracts18.2$Totalarea_Miles #calculate density as population/area


#make centroids of the houses and if centroid is in tract then add that data

# set random seed, basically the name giving to a paticular way to split data
set.seed(31356)

# get index for training sample can change 60-80
inTrain <- caret::createDataPartition(
  y = paste(dat_to_model$neighborhood), 
  p = .70, list = FALSE)
# split data into training and test
miami.training <- dat_to_model[inTrain,] 
miami.test     <- dat_to_model[-inTrain,]

Methods

In order to predict Sale Price, we first built and tested an algorithm which recognizes features of a home that would make it more likely to have a higher or lower price. In order to select which variables would become a part of this model, we used a â€œtrainingâ€ dataset to recognize variables with strong correlation to Sale Price, and testing this model on a â€œtestingâ€ dataset, which has all the same features, but on a set of homes the model hasnâ€™t yet predicted for.

Weâ€™re able to assess the overall performance of these algorithms be creating an average error in home price (plus or minus $20,000, for example). This error is known hereafter as Mean Absolute Error (MAE) or Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE). A lower average error in predicted home prices from the testing dataset would suggest that the model we create is strong. A higher error would suggest that the model is very weak.

After building a predictive model that performs to satisfaction, we will test the â€œgeneralizabilityâ€ of the model. This can be understood as the ability of the model to predict sale price with the same level of confidence (or equally distributed error) for any house, neighborhood, income group, or racial group.

Results

Overall, the results of this model are poor. The results of this model are very poor. This model predicts home price with an average error of $374,794.20.

This table shows the results of the regression model used to predict Sale Price. This table gives us insight to some key variables that are predictors for sale price. As an example interpretation of these results, we can estimate that, given a $62,710 baseline, the price of a home increases by $377 for every increase in square footage.

miami.test.reg1 <-
  miami.test %>%
  mutate(SalePrice.Predict = predict(reg1, miami.test),
         SalePrice.Error = SalePrice.Predict - SalePrice,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(SalePrice.Predict - SalePrice),
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(SalePrice.Predict - SalePrice)) / SalePrice.Predict)

miami.test.reg1$MAE <-mean(miami.test.reg1$SalePrice.AbsError, na.rm = T)

Generalizability

Next, we will test this model for generalizability. These new tests will also help us detect if this model has price errors that are clustered with one another. Based on the histogram below, we can see that our errors are not eveny distributed along a perfect â€œbell curveâ€. Furthermore, we still have a high MAE, this time at $400,977.40. The Model also notes that 68% of our predictions of home prices errors are within $153,290.7 of one another.

The Moranâ€™s I test below shows us that errors in price prediction of this model are clustered, not random as they should be. This might signify that there is an important variable missing from this study which would otherwise help errors remain consistent along price predictions.

#Moran's I test
coords <- st_coordinates(dat_to_model) 
neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
dat_to_model$lagPrice <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, dat_to_model$SalePrice)
coords.test <-  st_coordinates(miami.test) 
neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, 5))
spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W")

moranTest <- moran.mc(miami.test.reg1$SalePrice.Error, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "#FA7800",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in orange",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count",
       caption="Public Policy Analytics, Figure 6.8") +
  plotTheme()

### Generalizability by Income and Race

Finally, can test this modelâ€™s generalizability by both race and income. Tables below show the Mean Absolute Percentage Error for different income groups and homes with majority White residents.

Because the mean average percent error for residents in majority non-white neighborhoods is negative, this means the model systematically underpredicts home values for those in non-white neighborhoods. Conversely, the model systematically over-predicts values for homes in White neighborhoods.

Because the mean percent error for residenta is positive for â€œHigh Incomeâ€ groups, this means that this model systematically over-predicts home values for higher income neighborhoods and underpredicts for â€œLow Incomeâ€ groups.

tracts18_dem <-
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B01001_001E","B01001A_001E","B06011_001"),
          year=2018, state=12, county=086, geometry=T, output = "wide") %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102728')  %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001E,
         NumberWhites = B01001A_001E,
         Median_Income = B06011_001E) %>%
  mutate(percentWhite = NumberWhites / TotalPop,
         raceContext = ifelse(percentWhite > .5, "Majority White", "Majority Non-White"),
         incomeContext = ifelse(Median_Income > 32322, "High Income", "Low Income"))

Conclusion

Throughout this project, we have rigorously collected civic data from a variety of sources, analyzed characteristics of homes as they relate to home price, and attempted to model spatial factors that may relate to a homes value.

After this rigorous search and collection of relevant variables, we developed an algorithm and evaluated the algorithm for overall price error, as well as systematic errors as they relate to neighborhood, home value, income, and race in the city of Miami, FL.

Overall, this model has failed to pass such a rigorous test, but the methodology for testing was strong. It is not recommended that Zillow deploy this algorithm, but it will be imperative that, in future algorithms used by Zillow, they undergo reviews of error by all of the situations tested in this methodology. If given the opportunity to reproduce a better predictive model, it would be good for this model to incorporate more variables that impact public amenities and space throughout the city. This might include features related to zoning, local business, transportation, financial centers, or job centers.
